Assuming WinXP. Try this.
Run &quot;msconfig&quot; and  turn off all Startup programs ONLY via &quot;Selective
Startup&quot;by unchecking &quot;Load Startup Items&quot; After the mandatory reboot,
when you get back to the msconfig screen hit &quot;cancel&quot; . You have now
started up without any background programs running (hopefully). Also,
manually turn off any viruskillers that manage to elude &quot;msconfig&quot;.
Then restart Bioshock and see if the problem has disappeared. To get
back to normal just run &quot;msconfig&quot; again and select &quot;Normal Startup&quot;.

If that simple exercise does not work, I would recommend checking that
the X-Fi drivers are the latest.  Silly question -- you have
definitely completely turned off the A8NSLI on-board sound in BIOS??

John Lewis
