Oh, considering that you were the guy having so much trouble running
Bioshock in the first place, I consider it highly likely that one of
your installed programs running in background is VERY likely to be the
maverick giving you the grief with the sound as well.  Seems as if you
may have a bunch of badly-behaved programs running in background on
your system. Time for a full system clean-up?

And referring to my immediately preceding reply to your posting:-

If you are unnecessarily scared of running msconfig, just create a
System Restore point before running &quot;msconfig&quot;.  Also, I have one
critical professional program that I run on my system ( dual-core
4400+, A8N32-SLI) that is a very serious resource-hog and I have to
turn off all my background programs with &quot;msconfig&quot; for the program to
bootup and work normally.  A trivial exercise with &quot;msconfig&quot;. See the
sequence in my previous reply.  Just run &quot;msconfig&quot; again and select
&quot;normal startup&quot; to return to your normal state (after reboot).

